0128|- [HelpText]
0129|*Converting decimal numbers to fractions:
0130|*Examples:
0131|*   3.14159265(1:ratio).=3/1 (0.14159265)
0132|*   3.14159265(4:ratio).=16/5 (-0.05840735)
0133|*   3.14159265(5:ratio).=22/7 (-0.00126449285714)
0134|*   3.14159265(11:ratio).=355/113 (-0.00000027035398)
0135|*   3.14159265(20:ratio).=96893/30842 (0.00000001657804)
0136|*replaces the decimal number 3.14159265 by the best possible approximate
0137|*fraction (ratio of two integers) by using accuracies 1,4,5,11 and 20.
0138|*The numbers in parentheses are errors.
0140|*In x(c:ratio)=n/m,
0141|*the best approximation n/m for x is found by minimising the function
0143|*   f(x,m,n)=n+10^c*(m*x/n-1)^2
0145|*with respect to integers m and n. This technique is originally used
0146|*in S.Mustonen's studies for musical consonances and dissonances.
0147|*There x corresponds to a (impure) musical interval and the optimal
0148|*m and n values give the ideal ratio for the musical interval recognised
0149|*for a selected accuracy of the 'ear' c.
0151|*For example, the 'neutral third' 11/9=1.222222222
0152|*will be heard as an impure minor third (6/5) by a moderate ear c=4:
0153|*   1.222222222(4:ratio)=6/5 (0.022222222)
0154|*but as an interval of its own (11/9) by a very accurate ear c=5:
0155|*   1.222222222(5:ratio)=11/9 (-0.00000000022222)
